icestershire, England":"Loughborough, Leicestershire, England","Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England":"Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England","Willoughby, Loughborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Eresby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1230–1314":"1230–1314","1235–Female":"1235–Overleden","1250–1311":"1250–1311","1261–1325":"1261–1325","1260–1324":"1260–1324","1206–1248":"1206–1248","1210–1300":"1210–1300","about 1260":"circa 1260","about 1261":"circa 1261","before 1300":"vóór 1300","1230":"1230","1261":"1261","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1206":"1206","1248":"1248","1314":"1314","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1235":"1235","1311":"1311","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Loughborough, Leicestershire, England":"Loughborough, Leicestershire, England","Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England":"Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England","Willoughby, Loughborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Eresby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1230–1314":"1230–1314","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","1250–1311":"1250–1311","1261–1325":"1261–1325","1260–1324":"1260–1324","1206–1248":"1206–1248","1210–1300":"1210–1300","about 1260":"about 1260","about 1261":"about 1261","before 1300":"before 1300","1230":"1230","1261":"1261","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1206":"1206","1248":"1248","1314":"1314","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1235":"1235","1311":"1311","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Loughborough, Leicestershire, England":"Loughborough, Leicestershire, England","Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England":"Willoughby on the Wolds, Nottinghamshire, England","Willoughby, Loughborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Eresby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Willoughby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Willoughby, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, and Warwickshire. They are named from an Old English +<i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wilby","meanings":["habitational name from any of the places called Wilby, in Suffolk, Norfolk, and Northamptonshire. The first placename is probably named from an Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + Old English <i>bēag</i> ‘circle, ring’; the Norfolk placename derives from Old English <i>wilig</i> + <i>bēag</i> or Old Norse <i>bý</i> ‘farmstead, village’; the Northamptonshire placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Vili</i> + <i>bý</i>.","Redmonds has demonstrated that in the parish of Hipperholme, and subsequently elsewhere in Yorkshire, <i>Wilby</i> occurs as a variant of   Willoughby  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"W